# Why legacy-peer-deps (review finding M7, verified on the npm registry 2026-07-04):
# - What pins it: primeng 21.1.x declares peer @angular/* ^21 while this app runs Angular 22
#   — the combination is fixed by the stack manifest (docs/BOOTSTRAP.md §1, PrimeNG 21.1.x +
#   Angular 22.0.x, proven together in the parent project). The newest primeng still peers on
#   ^21, so there is no cleaner per-package pinning; npm ci needs this flag too (CI parity).
# - @angular/animations: deprecated upstream (Angular 22 native animate.enter/leave), but
#   still required by provideAnimationsAsync/PrimeNG. Latest is 22.x and this app pins ^22
#   (aligned with the workspace major).
# Remove this flag when PrimeNG ships an Angular 22 peer range.
legacy-peer-deps=true
